{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "Jonathan Edwards is a monist.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "He's not just a monist in the sense in which Hobbes or Berkeley is a monist - someone who believes that there's only one kind of substance - but a monist in the sense in which the great heretic Spinoza is a monist.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "There is, necessarily, only one substance.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Edwards's monism is part of a simple and beautiful system.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "God conserves the world in existence at each moment by an act that is equivalent to the act of creation.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Cause and effect cannot be located in different places or at different times.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Only God has power and thus only God is a true cause.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "God is the only genuine substance.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Nothing endures through time.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "There is no matter.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Properties must be upheld by something and asks what's doing the upholding, ultimately concluding that only God - and not matter - can uphold the properties of bodies.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "This yields the conclusion that there are no material substances and no powers thereof.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Edwards later generalizes the conclusion to the case of immaterial substance as well, thus ending up with no created powers and no created substance.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "The world exists only mentally, so that the very being of the world implies its being perceived or discovered.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "Edwards's argument for monism has three stages.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "In the first stage, he argues that bodies are nothing over and above resistance.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "In the second stage, Edwards adds that resistance must be upheld by something, and that the only thing that could uphold resistance is God.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "Thus Edwards concludes that there is no matter, a conclusion which reinforces his belief that God exists.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "In the third stage, he moves from immaterialism to monism, arguing that the powers and properties of minds - as well as bodies - can be upheld only by God.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "And, at this point, Edwards concludes that there are no created substances at all, only God.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
