{
  "ADUs": {
    "1": {
      "text": "The 18th-century Calvinist philosopher and theologian Jonathan Edwards is a monist. He's not just a monist in the sense in which Hobbes or Berkeley is a monist - someone who believes that there's only one kind of substance - but a monist in the sense in which the great heretic Spinoza is a monist. There is, necessarily, only one substance.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "2": {
      "text": "Edwards's monism is part of a simple and beautiful system. His fundamental ontology can be summed up by six, mainly negative, principles",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "3": {
      "text": "Continual creation. God conserves the world in existence at each moment by an act that is equivalent to the act of creation.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "4": {
      "text": "No action at a distance. Cause and effect cannot be located in different places or at different times.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "5": {
      "text": "No created powers. Only God has power and thus only God is a true cause.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "6": {
      "text": "No created substances. God is the only genuine substance.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "7": {
      "text": "No enduring things. Nothing endures through time.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "8": {
      "text": "No matter. There is no matter.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "9": {
      "text": "Edwards seems to have adopted this system in his early twenties and maintained it until his death.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "10": {
      "text": "One line of argument uses no action at a distance as its main premise, and infers continual creation and no enduring things from it. This line of argument supports no created substance and no created powers without quite implying them, for no action at a distance and no enduring things leave open the possibility of momentary substances that are immanent causes of their own states.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "11": {
      "text": "Here I'll consider the second line of argument. It starts with the notion that properties must be upheld by something and asks what's doing the upholding, ultimately concluding that only God - and not matter - can uphold the properties of bodies. This yields the conclusion that there are no material substances and no powers thereof.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
